AB  - The application of artificial intelligence (AI) in the field of energetic materials (EMs) has progressed from traditional machine learning to deep learning techniques, driving improvements in property prediction, molecular design, and combustion modeling. Despite these algorithmic advances, data engineering in EMs remains underdeveloped. Challenges related to data heterogeneity, inconsistency, and sensitivity continue to hinder the effective transition of AI from exploratory research to engineering practice and production-level deployment. This review examines the key bottlenecks in EM data engineering and discusses potential strategies, including the identification of reliable data sources, data augmentation, and automated annotation. Recent advances in large language models (LLMs), autonomous robotic chemists, and AI agents are highlighted for their potential in enhancing data acquisition, processing, labeling, and sharing. To address current limitations, we propose the development of a unified, secure, and open data infrastructure to support the scalable and trustworthy growth of data assets in the EM domain.
