AB  - As modern manufacturing systems demand increasing levels of complexity, flexibility, and intelligence, agent-based technologies are emerging as a key paradigm for enabling distributed control, adaptive decision-making, and collaborative autonomy. This paper presents a comprehensive review of the development trajectory and deployment pathways of agent systems in the context of smart manufacturing. Based on temporal evolution, the progression of agents is categorized into three major stages: Traditional Agents, AI Agents, and Agentic AI. To better elucidate the functional roles and technological advancements of various agent types within manufacturing systems, this study proposes a mapping framework grounded in the “cloud–edge–device” collaborative architecture. Four representative agent types are defined accordingly: Reactive Agents, Cooperative Agents, Cognitive Agents, and Agentic AI. Their core capabilities and typical application scenarios are systematically analyzed across different deployment layers. Furthermore, the paper synthesizes current research achievements, identifies critical technical challenges arising from trends such as Industry 5.0, large language models (LLMs), and cross-domain integration, and outlines future research directions. This review aims to provide a structured theoretical reference and a systematic cognitive framework for both research and practical implementation of agent technologies in smart manufacturing, thereby fostering the evolution of manufacturing systems toward greater autonomy, collaboration, and human-centricity.
