AB  - Creativity is an inherently social act, dependent on exchange, collaboration, and competition, with exposure to far-flung ideas one of its driving forces. Yet even as contemporary challenges increasingly require broad-based knowledge and linking arms across disciplines, creative pursuits are more and more walled off from each other. Large language models (LLMs) have the potential to facilitate collaboration by serving as boundary objects between fields, laying out common ground, serving as virtual icebreakers, and translating jargon. LLMs do not yet match the richness of human cognition, so using them effectively requires prompt engineering. But as tools in human hands, they offer an opportunity to build new communities of practice and drive convergence research.
